Nested Resource Competition Models

Ruby An

2023-02-01

1 One consumer, one resource

1.1 Equations

The basic set of equations for modeling one consumer (\(B\)) and one resource (\(R\)) are as follows.

\[ \begin{aligned} \frac{dB}{dt} &= f \frac{gR}{1+ ghR}B - m B \\ \frac{dR}{dt} &= r - \frac{gR}{1+ ghR}B \\ \end{aligned} \] Total biomass (\(B\)) is determined by the net balance between growth and loss rates. The growth rate per unit biomass is a function of resource availability, given by \(G(R) = f \frac{g R}{1+ g h R}\), where \(f\) is the resource conversion efficiency, \(g\) is uptake rate constant, and \(h\) controls the saturation rate of uptake. \(G(R)\) is linear when \(h = 0\), and saturates with increasing \(R\) when \(h > 0\). We assume a fixed loss rate \(m\) per unit biomass.

1.2 Equilibrium Solution (R*)

\(R^*\), or the minimum resource requirement, is the resource level \(R\) at which \(\frac{dB}{dt} = 0\). Graphically, this is where the growth rate curve \(G(R)\) curve crosses the loss-rate curve \(m\).
